1 the child may see or hear an act listed in this subsection (4).
2 (iii) "Partner" has the same meaning as provided in 45-5-206.
3 (c) Only the predominant aggressor, as determined by 46-6-311, may be charged under this
4 subsection (4).
5 (d) A charge under this subsection (4) is a separate offense and may be charged in addition to 45-
6 5-202, 45-5-206, 45-5-213, or 45-5-215. Each child identified in subsection (4)(a) may form the basis for
7 additional charges under this subsection (4).
8 (e) A person may be charged under this subsection (4) regardless of the child's relationship to the
9 person.
10 (5) A parent, guardian, or other person supervising the welfare of a child less than 16 years of age
11 may verbally or in writing request a person who is 18 years of age or older and who has no legal right of
12 supervision or control over the child to stop contacting the child if the requester believes that the contact is not
13 in the child's best interests. If the person continues to contact the child, the parent, guardian, or other person
14 supervising the welfare of the child may petition or the county attorney may upon the person's request petition
15 for an order of protection under Title 40, chapter 15. To the extent that they are consistent with this subsection,
16 the provisions of Title 40, chapter 15, apply. A person who purposely or knowingly violates an order of
17 protection commits the offense of endangering the welfare of children and upon conviction shall be sentenced
18 as provided in subsection (5)(a) (6)(a).
19 (6) (a) Except as provided in subsection (5) (b) (6)(b) or (6)(c), a person convicted of endangering
20 the welfare of children shall be fined an amount not to exceed $500 or be imprisoned in the county jail for any
21 term not to exceed 6 months, or both. A person convicted of a second offense of endangering the welfare of
22 children shall be fined an amount not to exceed $1,000 or be imprisoned in the county jail for any term not to
23 exceed 6 months, or both.
24 (b) A person convicted under subsection (3) is guilty of a felony and shall be imprisoned in the
25 state prison for a term not to exceed 5 years and may be fined an amount not to exceed $10,000, or both. If a
26 child suffers serious bodily injury, the offender shall be fined an amount not to exceed $25,000 or be imprisoned
27 for a term not to exceed 10 years, or both. Prosecution or conviction of a violation of subsection (3) does not
28 bar prosecution or conviction for any other crime committed by the offender as part of the same conduct.
